      "tabs": {
        "primary": {
          "body": "## **THE MAP OF MI'KMA'KI**\n\nLook at the map on the left. In 1752, Nova Scotia was not a province in the way we think of it today. [cite_start]It was **Mi'kma'ki**—the unceded ancestral territory of the Mi'kmaq people[cite: 17, 61]. The British were huddled in Halifax, outnumbered and desperate for peace. [cite_start]To survive, they signed the **Peace and Friendship Treaty of 1752**[cite: 17, 20]. \n\nThis wasn't a land surrender. It was a contract to share the territory. [cite_start]Central to this deal was the **Truckhouse**—a government trading post where Mi'kmaq could exchange their goods for British merchandise without being cheated by dishonest settlers[cite: 18, 20]. [cite_start]Leo argues that this Truckhouse promise created a permanent 'right to trade' that the province cannot simply ignore because centuries have passed[cite: 25, 26].",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/truckhouse-map.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        },
        "legal": {
          "body": "## **THE WORDS: 'ANY OTHER THING'**\n\nArticle 4 of the 1752 Treaty is the 'Smoking Gun' of Leo's defense. [cite_start]It grants the Mi'kmaq the right to sell 'Skins, feathers, fowl, fish or **ANY OTHER THING** they shall have to sell'[cite: 18, 19]. [cite_start]\n\nLeo's lawyers use the **'Living Tree' doctrine**, a core Canadian legal principle that says the Constitution must grow to fit modern times[cite: 21]. [cite_start]If 'Telegraphs' in the old law now includes the 'Internet,' then 'Skins and Feathers' must include 'Cannabis'[cite: 21, 25]. [cite_start]To 'freeze' the right in 1752 would be to treat Indigenous people like museum pieces rather than modern economic partners[cite: 22, 26].",
          "image": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/36/1752_Peace_and_Friendship_Treaty.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        },
        "intel": {
          [cite_start]"body": "## **THE WAMPUM ARCHIVE**\n\nThe British used ink; the Mi'kmaq used **Wampum Belts**[cite: 62]. [cite_start]These bead patterns are legal records of a 'Brother to Brother' relationship—not 'Subject to King'[cite: 63]. [cite_start]\n\nIntelligence analysts note that if the Wampum is the true record, the Mi'kmaq are **Sovereign Partners**[cite: 13, 15]. Partners don't need a license from their partner to do business on their own land. [cite_start]This evidence suggests that the Province's attempt to regulate Leo's shop is not just a policy choice, but a violation of the original equal partnership agreed upon in 1752[cite: 29, 87].",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/wampum-ai.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        }
      }
