      "shortTitle": "The Defense",
      "longTitle": "EXHIBIT C: Leo's Testimony",
      "interactionPrompt": "FIELD ANALYSIS (Cite evidence): Compare 'Muskets' (1760) to 'Cannabis' (2025). Is the analogy valid?",
      "options": ["Consider the Argument"],
      "tabs": {
        "primary": {
          [cite_start]"body": "## **THE EAGLE FEATHER OATH**\n\nLeo Francis takes the stand holding an **Eagle Feather**, symbolizing his oath to speak the absolute truth[cite: 62, 63]. He tells the court: 'For 200 years, you made us dependent on welfare. [cite_start]Now we found a way to fund our own elders' programs and fix our own roads, and you call us criminals'[cite: 25, 28]. [cite_start]\n\nLeo is fighting the **'Empty Box Theory'**[cite: 32]. [cite_start]The Crown says Indigenous rights are 'empty' until a judge says they exist[cite: 32, 33]. [cite_start]Leo says his box is **FULL** of inherent rights that were never given up—rights that existed long before Halifax was a single brick[cite: 71, 73].",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/heresleo-AI.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        },
        "legal": {
          [cite_start]"body": "## **THE SPARROW CHECKLIST**\n\nYou must guide the judge through the **Sparrow Test**[cite: 45]. \n1. [cite_start]**Is there a right?** (Yes, Treaty of 1752)[cite: 17]. \n2. [cite_start]**Was it broken?** (Yes, the raid)[cite: 65]. \n3. [cite_start]**Is it justified?**[cite: 45, 46]. [cite_start]\n\nThe Crown says 'Public Safety' justifies breaking the right[cite: 31, 111]. [cite_start]But under the **Sparrow Test**, the government must prove they used the 'least intrusive' method[cite: 45, 46]. [cite_start]If they could have just called the Chief to talk about safety instead of sending a SWAT team, then the raid was illegal because it wasn't 'minimally impairing'[cite: 46, 87].",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/sect35-1-ai.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        },
        "intel": {
          [cite_start]"body": "## **THE MUSKET ANALOGY**\n\nThe defense plays a historical 'Trump Card': **The Musket Precedent**[cite: 9, 26]. [cite_start]In 1760, the British traded **gunpowder, lead shot, and muskets** with the Mi'kmaq[cite: 17, 20]. [cite_start]\n\nIf the Treaty protected the trade of deadly weapons in 1760 because they were 'economic goods,' how can the Crown argue that a plant like cannabis is 'too dangerous' to trade today?[cite: 26, 86]. [cite_start]Combined with **UNDRIP Article 31**, which protects Indigenous plant medicines, this argument suggests that the Crown is using 'safety' as a colonial excuse to ban Mi'kmaw competition[cite: 87, 108].",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/1750-tradingpost.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        }
      }
    },
    {
