        "primary": {
          [cite_start]"body": "## **THE LAW COURTS**\n\nYou are standing in the halls of the Nova Scotia Law Courts[cite: 13]. [cite_start]Every judge here is haunted by the ghost of **Donald Marshall Jr.**[cite: 43]. [cite_start]\n\nIn 1999, Marshall was arrested for selling eels without a license[cite: 43, 44]. [cite_start]The Supreme Court eventually ruled he had a **Treaty Right** to fish for a 'moderate livelihood'[cite: 44, 120]. This case changed everything. [cite_start]It proved that Treaties are not just history—they are modern laws that can defeat provincial regulations[cite: 54, 55]. [cite_start]Leo argues he is the 'Marshall of Cannabis,' trying to earn the same livelihood promised 270 years ago[cite: 25, 28].",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/Supreme_Court_of_Nova_Scotia_in_2018-Wikimedia.jpg",
          "credit": "wikimedia"
        },
        "legal": {
          [cite_start]"body": "## **MODERATE LIVELIHOOD**\n\nWhat is a **Moderate Livelihood**?[cite: 44]. [cite_start]The Supreme Court defined it as the ability to pay for 'necessaries' like food, clothing, and housing—but not to become a millionaire[cite: 44, 120]. [cite_start]\n\nThe Crown argues Leo's shop is too big to be 'moderate'[cite: 30, 31]. [cite_start]They say he is running a commercial enterprise, not a survival-based trade[cite: 44, 47]. [cite_start]Leo counters that to fix a community's roads and schools, you need a modern economy, not just enough to buy bread[cite: 25, 28]. [cite_start]The line between 'necessaries' and 'wealth' is the razor's edge this case rests on[cite: 29, 44].",
          "image": "http://dwaugh-edsim.github.io/projectimages/leo-sitroom2/images/marshall-1.jpg",
          "credit": "AI"
        },
        "intel": {
          [cite_start]"body": "## **THE SPARROW FLOWCHART**\n\nLook at the **Sparrow Test Flowchart** on the left[cite: 45]. [cite_start]This is the 'Logic Bomb' that can destroy the Crown's case[cite: 45]. [cite_start]\n\nStep 3: **Was there consultation?**[cite: 46]. [cite_start]Intelligence shows that the Province never called the Chief before the raid[cite: 94, 107]. [cite_start]They didn't try to co-develop safety rules; they just sent the police[cite: 111, 113]. [cite_start]Under the **Honour of the Crown**, the government must speak to its partners before breaking their rights[cite: 75, 94]. [cite_start]Because they didn't, the raid might be illegal even if the Crown's 'safety' concerns were real[cite: 94].",
